<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-281-461  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 281 461.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Jan 23 1989 v216 n4 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Super bowl ads kick off 'new' ATandamp;T long-distance push.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Harper, Maribeth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Joseph Nacchio, ATandamp;T's new VP-Business Services, is planningpromotions, beginning Super Bowl Sunday, Jan 22, 1989, that areintended to transform ATandamp;T's 'Ma Bell' image to one of a dynamic,innovative and competitive company.andP;  Ads will initially targetsmall businesses and will offer a 90-day no-risk trial of Pro-WATSservices, with a $10 sign-up charge waived between Jan 22 and Mar15, 1989.andP;  The program, already approved by the FCC, willreimburse users of ATandamp;T's Pro-WATS I, II and III for localexchange charges incurred when they change to ATandamp;T.andP;  And customersget refunds if they try ATandamp;T and decide to go back to anotherlong-distance provider.andP;  The program is an example of ATandamp;T'sefforts to recapture an eroding business customer market share.andO;Nacchio estimates that ATandamp;T lost $100 million in 1988 to MCITelecommunications Corp, US Sprint and regional long-distancecompanies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     Telephone companiesCommunications Service SuppliersPromotion of ProductCompetitionImageUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionGovernment RegulationPrice CuttingManagement StyleMarket ShareLossesSales.andO;Person:    Nacchio, Joseph (management).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>